    <section id="strategies">
        <div class="section-header">
            <div class="section-tag">02 // Strategy Case Studies</div>
            <h2 class="section-title">Honest Research, Not Polished Wins</h2>
            <p class="section-desc">
                Four strategies spanning volatility, momentum, and statistical arbitrage. 
                I emphasize what broke, where I was wrong, and what I would do differently — 
                because in quant research, the failures teach more than the wins.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="strategy-grid">
            <!-- STRATEGY 1: VIX Carry -->
            <div class="strategy-card">
                <div class="strategy-header">
                    <div class="card-header">
                        <div>
                            <span style="display:inline-block;background:rgba(16,185,129,0.15);color:#10b981;font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.7rem;padding:0.25rem 0.75rem;border-radius:100px;font-weight:500;">Live Paper Trading</span>
                            <h3 style="font-size:1.35rem;font-weight:700;margin-top:0.75rem;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Short Volatility Carry with VIX Term Structure</h3>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:0.95rem;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Sell short-dated VIX futures when term structure is in contango, hedge with long SPY puts. Harvest volatility risk premium while protecting against tail events.</p>
                    <div class="metrics-grid">
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value positive">1.42</div><div class="metric-label">Sharpe</div></div>
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value negative">-12.3%</div><div class="metric-label">Max DD</div></div>
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value neutral">68%</div><div class="metric-label">Win Rate</div></div>
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value neutral">1,247</div><div class="metric-label">Trades</div></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="strategy-body">
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Hypothesis</h4>
                        <p>VIX futures consistently trade at a premium to realized volatility due to investor demand for crash protection. By selling the front-month VIX future when the term structure is in steep contango (M1/M2 &gt; 1.15), we capture the roll-down yield while maintaining delta-neutral exposure via SPY put spreads.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Data & Methodology</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Data:</strong> CBOE VIX futures daily settle (2004-2024), SPY options chain from ORATS, 1-minute SPY tick for slippage estimation</li>
                            <li><strong>Signal:</strong> M1/M2 contango ratio &gt; 1.15 + VIX &lt; 25 (avoid regime shifts)</li>
                            <li><strong>Position:</strong> Short 1 VX1 contract, long 0.3 delta SPY put spread 30 DTE</li>
                            <li><strong>Rebalance:</strong> Daily at 3:45 PM ET, roll 5 days before expiration</li>
                            <li><strong>Costs:</strong> $2.50/contract RT commission, 0.5bp slippage on entry/exit</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Backtest Results</h4>
                        <p>CAGR: 14.2% | Volatility: 10.1% | Sortino: 2.1 | Calmar: 1.15. Strategy performed well in 2012-2017 and 2021-2023 but suffered during Feb 2018 VIX spike (-8.4% in 2 days) and March 2020 COVID crash (-12.3% max drawdown).</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="failure-box">
                        <h5>⚠ What Broke</h5>
                        <p><strong>Feb 2018 Volmageddon:</strong> The VIX term structure inverted in hours. My contango filter (M1/M2 &gt; 1.15) kept me in the trade because the ratio was 1.12 at 2:30 PM — above my threshold. By 4:00 PM, VIX futures had spiked 100%. The lesson: <em>term structure filters react too slowly for gap risk</em>. I now use an intraday VIX momentum brake (halt new positions if VIX moves &gt;20% from open).</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="improvement-box">
                        <h5>🔧 What I Would Change Next</h5>
                        <p>1) Add a volatility regime classifier (GARCH(1,1) forecast vs realized) to reduce position size in high-uncertainty periods. 2) Replace SPY put spreads with VIX call spreads for purer tail hedge. 3) Test dynamic position sizing based on Kelly criterion rather than fixed notional.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- STRATEGY 2: Order Flow Momentum -->
            <div class="strategy-card">
                <div class="strategy-header">
                    <div class="card-header">
                        <div>
                            <span style="display:inline-block;background:rgba(245,158,11,0.15);color:#f59e0b;font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.7rem;padding:0.25rem 0.75rem;border-radius:100px;font-weight:500;">Paused — Under Review</span>
                            <h3 style="font-size:1.35rem;font-weight:700;margin-top:0.75rem;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Intraday Momentum with Order Flow Imbalance</h3>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:0.95rem;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Use bid-ask imbalance and trade sign classification to predict 5-minute directional moves in S&P 500 e-mini futures. Machine-learned signal on Level 2 order book features.</p>
                    <div class="metrics-grid">
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value neutral">0.89</div><div class="metric-label">Sharpe</div></div>
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value negative">-18.7%</div><div class="metric-label">Max DD</div></div>
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value neutral">54%</div><div class="metric-label">Win Rate</div></div>
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value neutral">8,942</div><div class="metric-label">Trades</div></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="strategy-body">
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Hypothesis</h4>
                        <p>Large market orders that consume multiple price levels create temporary order flow imbalance. By measuring bid-ask pressure (volume at bid vs ask) and trade sign classification (Lee-Ready algorithm), we can predict short-term price direction before the imbalance resolves.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Data & Methodology</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Data:</strong> CME ES futures Level 2 tick data (2019-2024), 5-minute bars with 20 order book features</li>
                            <li><strong>Features:</strong> Bid-ask imbalance, trade sign ratio, depth asymmetry, cancellation rate, quote intensity</li>
                            <li><strong>Model:</strong> XGBoost classifier (tuned via walk-forward CV), probability threshold 0.58 for trade entry</li>
                            <li><strong>Execution:</strong> Market orders with 1-tick slippage assumption, $1.25/contract RT</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Backtest Results</h4>
                        <p>In-sample (2019-2022): Sharpe 1.34, win rate 61%. Out-of-sample (2023-2024): Sharpe collapsed to 0.89, win rate 54%. The model degraded significantly after Q2 2023 when CME changed tick size rules for ES futures.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="failure-box">
                        <h5>⚠ What Broke</h5>
                        <p><strong>Regime Change + Overfitting:</strong> I used 3 years of in-sample data with walk-forward CV, but the feature importance was dominated by quote intensity — a feature that changed meaning after the CME tick size reduction from 0.25 to 0.05 index points. The model learned a microstructure pattern that no longer existed. Worse, I did not catch this in paper trading because I used simulated fills instead of live market data for the first 2 months. <em>This is survivorship bias in real time: I was testing on data that no longer reflected market reality.</em></p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="improvement-box">
                        <h5>🔧 What I Would Change Next</h5>
                        <p>1) Use purely out-of-sample validation with a 6-month "no-touch" holdout period before any capital deployment. 2) Add feature stability monitoring — if feature importance shifts &gt;30% month-over-month, halt trading. 3) Replace XGBoost with an online learning approach (River library) that adapts to microstructure changes. 4) Use live paper trading with real market data from day one, not simulated fills.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- STRATEGY 3: Cross-Asset Momentum -->
            <div class="strategy-card">
                <div class="strategy-header">
                    <div class="card-header">
                        <div>
                            <span style="display:inline-block;background:rgba(139,92,246,0.15);color:#8b5cf6;font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.7rem;padding:0.25rem 0.75rem;border-radius:100px;font-weight:500;">Research Phase</span>
                            <h3 style="font-size:1.35rem;font-weight:700;margin-top:0.75rem;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Cross-Asset Momentum with Volatility-Adjusted Sizing</h3>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:0.95rem;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Apply time-series momentum across equities, bonds, commodities, and FX with volatility targeting (10% annualized) and dynamic correlation-based position limits.</p>
                    <div class="metrics-grid">
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value positive">1.18</div><div class="metric-label">Sharpe</div></div>
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value negative">-15.4%</div><div class="metric-label">Max DD</div></div>
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value neutral">56%</div><div class="metric-label">Win Rate</div></div>
                        <div class="metric"><div class="metric-value neutral">2,160</div><div class="metric-label">Trades</div></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="strategy-body">
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Hypothesis</h4>
                        <p>Time-series momentum (trend-following) exists across asset classes but with varying speeds. By pooling signals across 40+ futures markets and volatility-adjusting position sizes, we achieve diversification benefits that improve risk-adjusted returns beyond any single asset.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Data & Methodology</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Data:</strong> Daily futures prices from Quandl/CHRIS (1990-2024), 12 asset classes, 43 markets</li>
                            <li><strong>Signal:</strong> 12-month minus 1-month return (classic Moskowitz-Grinblatt momentum)</li>
                            <li><strong>Sizing:</strong> Volatility targeting at 10% annualized using 60-day realized vol</li>
                            <li><strong>Correlation cap:</strong> Maximum 15% portfolio risk from any single asset class</li>
                            <li><strong>Costs:</strong> 2bp per trade, $5/contract RT, 0.1% annual management fee proxy</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Backtest Results</h4>
                        <p>CAGR: 11.8% | Volatility: 10.0% | Sharpe: 1.18 | Max DD: -15.4% (Mar 2020). The strategy struggled in 2009-2012 (post-crisis choppy markets) and 2022 (simultaneous bond/equity drawdown — correlation breakdown).</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="failure-box">
                        <h5>⚠ What Broke</h5>
                        <p><strong>Correlation Assumption Failure:</strong> My correlation-based position limits assumed historical pairwise correlations were stable. In 2022, equity-bond correlation flipped from -0.2 to +0.6 — the first time in 20 years. My position limit logic <em>increased</em> bond exposure because the "diversification benefit" looked attractive historically. Result: simultaneous losses in both legs. I also discovered lookahead bias in my volatility calculation: I used 60-day realized vol but rebalanced monthly, meaning the last 30 days of vol data overlapped with the return period I was targeting. This artificially improved Sharpe by ~0.15.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="improvement-box">
                        <h5>🔧 What I Would Change Next</h5>
                        <p>1) Use exponentially-weighted correlation with 90-day half-life instead of full-sample historical. 2) Add a correlation regime detector (HMM) that reduces position sizes when cross-asset correlation becomes unstable. 3) Fix the lookahead bias by using vol estimated from t-60 to t-30 for position sizing at time t. 4) Test with actual ETF data instead of continuous futures to account for roll costs and contango/backwardation effects.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

