                <div class="strategy-body">
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Hypothesis</h4>
                        <p>Academic research (e.g., Gao et al., 2018) suggests options markets systematically underprice earnings announcement risk. By buying ATM straddles just before earnings and selling immediately after, we capture the volatility expansion without directional exposure.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Data & Methodology</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Data:</strong> ORATS options surface for S&P 500 constituents (2015-2024), earnings dates from Bloomberg</li>
                            <li><strong>Signal:</strong> Stocks with implied earnings move &lt; 5% (cheap vol) and average post-earnings move &gt; 7% (historical edge)</li>
                            <li><strong>Entry:</strong> Buy ATM straddle at close T-2, delta-hedge at entry</li>
                            <li><strong>Exit:</strong> Sell at market open T+1 (post-earnings)</li>
                            <li><strong>Costs:</strong> $0.65/contract RT, 5% slippage on entry/exit (wide bid-ask pre-earnings)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="strategy-section">
                        <h4>Backtest Results</h4>
                        <p>Sharpe: -0.34 | Win rate: 38% | Max DD: -42%. The strategy lost money consistently. Post-hoc analysis showed the "edge" disappeared after 2019 as more market participants began trading earnings vol, compressing the mispricing.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="failure-box">
                        <h5>⚠ What Broke</h5>
                        <p><strong>Multiple Biases + Crowded Trade:</strong> This was my first strategy and it was riddled with errors: (1) <em>Survivorship bias</em> — I only tested on current S&P 500 constituents, ignoring delisted stocks that likely had worse earnings outcomes. (2) <em>Lookahead bias</em> — I used earnings dates from a database that was updated retrospectively; in live trading, earnings date changes would have caused missed entries. (3) <em>Transaction cost fantasy</em> — I assumed 5% slippage but actual pre-earnings bid-ask spreads were often 15-20% of premium for illiquid names. (4) The strategy was a crowded trade by 2020; the alpha was arbitraged away. <em>This failure taught me more than any successful backtest.</em></p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="improvement-box">
                        <h5>🔧 What I Would Change Next</h5>
                        <p>1) Use point-in-time S&P 500 membership to eliminate survivorship bias. 2) Build an earnings date uncertainty model (some companies pre-announce, delay, or change dates). 3) Use only liquid options (open interest &gt;1000, bid-ask &lt;5%). 4) Instead of buying straddles, explore selling iron condors on names with historically overpriced earnings vol — the opposite side of the same trade. 5) Most importantly: <em>never deploy a strategy without 6 months of live paper trading on real market data.</em></p>
