    <section id="risk">
        <div class="section-header">
            <div class="section-tag">04 // Risk & Bias Awareness</div>
            <h2 class="section-title">I Know What I Do Not Know</h2>
            <p class="section-desc">
                Quantitative research is a minefield of subtle biases. Here is how I think about them — 
                and a concrete example of catching myself in a classic trap.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="risk-grid">
            <div class="risk-card">
                <h4>🔮 Lookahead Bias</h4>
                <p>Using information that would not be available at the time of the trading decision. My defense: strict point-in-time data requirements, lag all fundamental data by 1 reporting period, and never use future information for imputation.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="risk-card">
                <h4>⚰️ Survivorship Bias</h4>
                <p>Testing only on stocks that still exist, ignoring delisted companies that likely performed worse. My defense: use CRSP/Compustat merged database with delisting returns, or at minimum adjust for known survivorship in free data.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="risk-card">
                <h4>🎯 Overfitting</h4>
                <p>Optimizing parameters to noise rather than signal. My defense: walk-forward optimization with expanding windows, minimum 30% out-of-sample holdout, and penalizing model complexity via AIC/BIC.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="risk-card">
                <h4>💸 Transaction Costs</h4>
                <p>Assuming frictionless markets. My defense: model slippage as function of volatility and volume, include market impact for positions &gt;1% ADV, and stress-test with 2x assumed costs.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="catch-box">
            <h4>🎣 How I Caught Myself: The Earnings Straddle Lookahead Bias</h4>
            <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);margin-bottom:1rem;">
                In my first earnings volatility strategy (Strategy 4 above), I was using an earnings calendar dataset 
                that I downloaded in 2024. The dataset included "actual" earnings dates — which were updated 
                retrospectively if companies changed their announced date. In live trading, I would have been 
                using the <em>announced</em> date, which sometimes changed. I caught this when I noticed that 
                my backtest entry dates matched the "actual" dates perfectly — too perfectly.
            </p>
            <pre>"""
BUGGY CODE (what I wrote initially):
    earnings_date = calendar.loc[ticker, 'earnings_date']  # "Actual" date from 2024 dataset
    entry_date = earnings_date - pd.Timedelta(days=2)

FIXED CODE (what it should be):
    # Use only information available at time t
    announced_date = calendar_as_of(t).loc[ticker, 'announced_date']
    # Some companies delay earnings — we only know the announced date at time t
    if announced_date != actual_date:
        # We would have missed the trade or entered wrong
        entry_date = announced_date - pd.Timedelta(days=2)

# Result: Sharpe dropped from 0.12 to -0.34 after fixing this bias.
# The "strategy" was never profitable — I had been curve-fitting to 
# perfect foresight of earnings dates.
"""</pre>
            <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);margin-top:1rem;">
                <strong>Lesson:</strong> Always ask "would I have known this at the time?" If the answer is no, 
                the backtest is lying to you. This single fix turned a "marginal" strategy into a clear failure — 
                which is exactly the kind of honest result that saves you from losing real money.
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>

